						               													<description>&amp;#233;&amp;#173;&amp;#148;&amp;#229;&amp;#176;&amp;#142;&amp;#229;&amp;#163;&amp;#171;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#174;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#168;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#172;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#179;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#172; (Wizard's Element Collection) is a roll and move, set collection game from Japan. Wizards move around the edge of the Elemental field, and try to capture elements to make even pairs.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game has a deck of 68 Elements in 12 different types (such as Heart, Wind, Earth, Brass...). These are shuffled and a 3x3 grid is dealt out. A set of 16 Mass discs are placed around the grid, in line with all the rows, columns and diagonals. The players move their wizards around the discs using dice rolls, and point along the line they want to collect from.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Where wizards want to take the same card from the grid, the priority is based on the Mass disc they stand on. But the Elements carry special effects, and cards already taken by a Wizard can be used to strengthen their priority.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Wizards are trying to build an even collection to gain positive scores. Odd sets will lose points.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;As cards are taken from the grid, they are replaced until the deck is exhausted. The wizard with the highest score is the winner.&amp;#10;user summary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
